ing:   o Army in Europe conducting combat medic training using live animals   o Basing and unit restructure and realignment initiatives including the move of the U.S. Army Europe headquarters to Wiesbaden   o The impact on the Army in Europe of the Quadrennial Defense Review   o The command’s transition from the NSPS personnel system to the GS personnel system   o Routine issues affecting the command and its personnel• Responded to numerous media queries:   o Soldier deaths in Afghanistan, Iraq, and in Europe   o The crash of a U.S. Army Europe helicopter resulting in the deaths of three Soldiers   o Suicides and suicide prevention   o Sexual harassment and assault prevention   o Controversial basing and unit transformation actions   o Routine issues affecting the command and its personnel• Attended the week-long Georgetown University Congressional Operations SeminarMedia Relations Lead (Public Affairs Specialist GS12) at U.S. Army EuropeU.S. Army Europe Public AffairsSeptember 2006  –  December 2009 (3 years 4 months)• Led U.S. Army media relations operations during the 65th annual commemoration of the D-Day landings at Normandy, France.   o  Supervised media operations at more than 20 commemoration events.    o More than 500 media representatives attended the main event at the Normandy American Cemetery alone.• Responded to numerous media queries on high-visibility, politically sensitive issues:    o Multiple-death helicopter crash in Italy   o General Officer under investigation   o Reports of a suspected terrorist action at a high-visibility U.S. Army Europe installation   o Deserter seeking asylum in Germany   o Force protection concerns during periods of increased terrorist threat   o Arab-speaking Civilians on the Battlefield used at our training center   o Operation Iraqi Freedom/Operation Enduring Freedom casualties   o Suicides and suicide prevention   o Sexual assault prevention training   o Controversial organizational transformation actions• Planned and